---
/**
 * context-engineering 0005 · Figure 1 — the pre-indexed ↔ read-on-demand
 * spectrum (HERO).
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from
 * docs/context-engineering/lessons/0005-architecture-reviews-and-production-design.html
 * (figure + svg + figcaption incl. the footnote <sup>). It lives as an .astro
 * component, NOT inline in the MDX, because MDX's JSX parser is unreliable with
 * raw inline SVG that uses kebab-case attributes (text-anchor, font-size,
 * stroke-width, marker-end, …).
 *
 * The source page declared the arrowhead markers (#arw / #arwG / #arwM / #arwR)
 * ONCE in a global <svg defs> at the top of <body>; in the standalone component
 * world each figure carries its own <defs> for the markers it references — here
 * only #arw — so the SVG renders self-contained. Marker fills match the source.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 300"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Four AI products placed on a spectrum from pre-indexed retrieval to read-on-demand, each with its own failure mode."
    >
        <defs>
            <marker
                id="arw"
                viewBox="0 0 10 10"
                refX="8.5"
                refY="5"
                markerWidth="7"
                markerHeight="7"
                orient="auto-start-reverse"
                ><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 z" fill="#6b675f"></path></marker
            >
        </defs>
        <text x="320" y="20" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12.5" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Every assistant lives on one spectrum</text
        >
        <!-- spectrum line -->
        <line
            x1="60"
            y1="120"
            x2="580"
            y2="120"
            stroke="#6b675f"
            stroke-width="2"
            marker-start="url(#arw)"
            marker-end="url(#arw)"></line>
        <text x="64" y="142" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="#1f3a5a"
            >PRE-INDEXED (embeddings)</text
        >
        <text x="576" y="142" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >READ-ON-DEMAND (tools)</text
        >
        <!-- product nodes -->
        <rect x="80" y="56" width="120" height="40" rx="8" fill="#eef2f7" stroke="#1f3a5a"
        ></rect><text
            x="140"
            y="74"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10.5"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#1f3a5a">Cursor</text
        ><text x="140" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >repo embeddings</text
        >
        <rect x="222" y="56" width="120" height="40" rx="8" fill="#f6eef7" stroke="#b5179e"
        ></rect><text
            x="282"
            y="74"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10.5"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#b5179e">Copilot</text
        ><text x="282" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >open files + index</text
        >
        <rect x="364" y="56" width="120" height="40" rx="8" fill="#f6eef7" stroke="#b5179e"
        ></rect><text
            x="424"
            y="74"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10.5"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#b5179e">ChatGPT</text
        ><text x="424" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >history + connectors</text
        >
        <rect x="478" y="56" width="120" height="40" rx="8" fill="#e9f3ec" stroke="#2f5d3a"
        ></rect><text
            x="538"
            y="74"
            text-anchor="middle"
            font-size="10.5"
            font-weight="700"
            fill="#2f5d3a">Claude Code</text
        ><text x="538" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >grep / glob / read</text
        >
        <!-- tethers -->
        <line x1="140" y1="96" x2="140" y2="118" stroke="#6b675f"></line>
        <line x1="282" y1="96" x2="282" y2="118" stroke="#6b675f"></line>
        <line x1="424" y1="96" x2="424" y2="118" stroke="#6b675f"></line>
        <line x1="538" y1="96" x2="538" y2="118" stroke="#6b675f"></line>
        <!-- failure-mode row -->
        <text x="320" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >…and each position picks its own way to fail</text
        >
        <rect x="40" y="192" width="560" height="80" rx="8" fill="#fbecec" stroke="#9a2417"></rect>
        <text x="56" y="214" font-size="9.5" fill="#9a2417"
            ><tspan font-weight="700">Pre-indexed:</tspan> stale index · retrieves a topically-similar
            but wrong file · misses exact identifiers</text
        >
        <text x="56" y="234" font-size="9.5" fill="#9a2417"
            ><tspan font-weight="700">Read-on-demand:</tspan> latency &amp; token cost from round-trips
            · misses a file it never thought to grep</text
        >
        <text x="56" y="254" font-size="9.5" fill="#9a2417"
            ><tspan font-weight="700">History / none:</tspan> weak grounding in live systems · hallucinates
            when nothing was retrieved</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        The reviewer's first move on any AI product: place it on the <b
            >pre-indexed &harr; read-on-demand</b
        > spectrum. Position predicts failure mode — staleness on the left, missed-grep and cost on the
        right, hallucination at the "none" extreme. Product specifics here are <em
            >at time of writing</em
        > and version-dependent.<sup><a href="#s4" id="r4">4</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
